Both de Chirico and Dali (and maybe all great painters) had very gastronomic thinking and were obsessed with specific foods like snails or oysters in terms of texture, contours, etc. Chirico writes he had an "innate aversion to all flabby substances lacking an internal armature."

D. Galkovsky's "Noviop" concept (Noviop: the raceless men mass-produced in the USSR out of Armenians, Uzbeks, Georgians, Jewishy-ish groups, etc.)  dates to Romans accusing their lessers of "having no race". Per Evola: "He who has no race does not know dangerous [romantic] love."

The same constitutional armature that ensures one's loyalty to the nation, religion, rulership, etc. - being Russian in this case - is also what ensures his capability of Eros, love, deep passions, etc. Having his Russian-ness dismantled leaves one able to only grasp at surfaces.

Bolshevism's racially disarmed people (the noviops of Galkovsky) are by the nature of their condition not only left without loyalty to their nation (thus making an ideal new political class to rule without any sentimental attachment) but also with a fundamental inability to love.
